      "Essential mineral; the **fourth most abundant cation in the body** and a cofactor for **>600 enzymatic reactions** including ATP synthesis (every ATP molecule must bind Mg²⁺ to be biologically active — Mg-ATP is the actual functional form), DNA/RNA synthesis, protein synthesis, glucose metabolism, and neurotransmitter regulation. **Mechanism — universal cofactor**: magnesium is required for the function of every cell in the body. ATP without bound Mg²⁺ is biologically inert; the entire energy metabolism of every cell depends on adequate intracellular magnesium. The mineral also stabilizes DNA structure, supports DNA replication and repair, regulates calcium channel function (counterbalancing calcium's excitatory effects), modulates NMDA glutamate receptor activity (preventing excitotoxicity), and supports parathyroid hormone function and vitamin D activation. **Mechanism — distribution**: ~99% of body magnesium is intracellular (60% in bone, 39% in soft tissue), only ~1% is in serum/plasma. **This distribution makes serum magnesium testing a poor indicator of total-body status** — serum levels can be normal while tissues are depleted; RBC magnesium and intracellular magnesium tests are more informative but less commonly run. Tissue magnesium depletion is widespread in the modern population yet often invisible to standard lab work. **Mechanism — RDA-vs-actual-need gap**: the official RDA is 400–420mg/day for adult men, 310–320mg/day for adult women — these values reflect minimums to prevent overt deficiency, not optimum for performance, sleep, or longevity. Modern food-chain magnesium content has dropped substantially over decades (soil depletion, processing, refining); the modal Western intake is 250–300mg/day from food, well below RDA, and even RDA-meeting intakes may be inadequate for active populations, athletes, users on diuretics or PPIs, alcohol users, and aging individuals. **Mechanism — clinical and subclinical deficiency consequences**: muscle cramps and twitches, restless leg syndrome, fatigue, sleep disruption (particularly difficulty staying asleep), anxiety and irritability, cardiac arrhythmias, hypertension, insulin resistance, migraines, osteoporosis acceleration, increased systemic inflammation. **The evidence base for magnesium supplementation is one of the strongest of any supplement category** — multiple meta-analyses support benefit in sleep, anxiety, cardiovascular outcomes, migraine prevention, and metabolic markers. **Mechanism — form selection (the central practical decision)**: oral magnesium absorption varies dramatically by form. The bound molecule (glycinate, malate, threonate, oxide, etc.) determines: (1) absorption percentage, (2) tissue distribution, (3) tolerability (GI effects), (4) which secondary benefit accompanies the magnesium. **Form selection is more consequential than dose for magnesium supplementation.** Taking 800mg of oxide delivers less elemental magnesium than 200mg of glycinate, and the oxide produces GI distress while the glycinate produces sleep benefits — the same total milligram count, completely different outcomes.",
