    mechanism:
      "The smallest and structurally simplest amino acid (a single hydrogen atom as its side chain) and one of the **most multifunctional molecules in human biology**. Glycine is technically classified as 'conditionally essential' — humans synthesize it endogenously, but synthesis capacity is often inadequate to meet biological demand, particularly in users with high collagen turnover, methylation demands, or stress-driven glutathione consumption. The recommended endogenous synthesis estimate (~3g/day) is well below estimated daily need (~10–15g/day), creating a substantial gap that dietary intake fills inadequately for most modern eaters. **Mechanism — collagen building block (the largest single use)**: glycine constitutes ~33% of all collagen amino acids — roughly every third position in the collagen triple-helix is glycine. The body synthesizes ~2g of collagen-bound glycine per day; insufficient glycine availability constrains collagen synthesis, contributing to skin, connective tissue, joint, and vascular wall integrity decline. Modern Western diets that emphasize muscle meat over collagen-rich tissues (skin, connective tissue, bone broth, gelatin) are systematically glycine-deficient relative to ancestral patterns where whole-animal eating provided substantial collagen-derived glycine. **Mechanism — methylation buffer (the under-appreciated function)**: glycine is the substrate for **glycine N-methyltransferase (GNMT)**, an enzyme that consumes excess methyl groups by methylating glycine to sarcosine. This buffers the methylation pool — when SAMe (S-adenosylmethionine, the universal methyl donor) levels are high, GNMT prevents excessive methylation by 'dumping' methyl groups onto glycine. Inadequate glycine availability disrupts methylation balance, contributing to a range of subtle methylation-related symptoms (mood, energy, cognitive function). **Mechanism — sleep architecture support (the most subjectively perceptible effect)**: glycine acts as an inhibitory neurotransmitter at glycine receptors (concentrated in spinal cord and brainstem) and modulates NMDA receptor activity. Oral glycine 3g pre-bed produces measurable improvements in sleep quality, particularly subjective sleep quality, daytime fatigue reduction, and slow-wave sleep architecture (Yamadera 2007, Bannai 2012). The mechanism appears to involve both direct neurotransmitter effects and a paradoxical mild peripheral vasodilation that lowers core body temperature (a permissive condition for sleep onset). **Mechanism — glutathione synthesis substrate**: glycine is one of the three amino acids (cysteine, glutamate, glycine) that combine to form glutathione, the body's master antioxidant. Cysteine availability is usually the rate-limiting step for glutathione synthesis (the basis for NAC supplementation), but glycine availability becomes limiting under conditions of high glutathione demand. **Mechanism — bile acid conjugation**: glycine conjugates bile acids in the liver, supporting fat digestion and lipid metabolism. **Mechanism — anti-inflammatory effects**: emerging evidence for glycine's anti-inflammatory effects via glycine receptor modulation in immune cells. **Pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability excellent (~95%); plasma peak ~30–60 minutes; sweet taste makes powder forms easy to consume.",
