      "OTC supplement; widely available. Pharmaceutical-grade glycine is essentially a commodity — quality differences between reputable brands modest. Reputable brands: Now Foods Glycine, BulkSupplements Glycine Powder, Pure Encapsulations Glycine, Designs for Health Glycine. **Powder forms substantially more cost-effective** than capsules for users running 5g+ daily (capsules typically 500mg–1g per cap; reaching 5g/day requires many capsules; powder mixes easily with water and tastes sweet). Cost: powder ~$10–25 for 1kg+ supply (months of use at typical doses); capsules more expensive per gram.",
    notes:
      "## Glycine Use Cases — The Multifunctional Foundation\n\nGlycine is one of the most underrated foundational supplements because it addresses multiple distinct use cases simultaneously:\n\n1. **Sleep optimization** (3g pre-bed) — measurable RCT evidence\n2. **Collagen / connective tissue support** (5–10g/day) — skin, joints, vascular wall\n3. **Methylation buffer** (via GNMT) — prevents over-methylation\n4. **Glutathione substrate** — antioxidant pathway support\n5. **Bile acid conjugation** — fat digestion support\n\nThe multifunctional nature means glycine supplementation often produces benefits across multiple domains simultaneously — better sleep + skin / joint improvements + subtle methylation balance over months.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nGlycine 3g pre-bed × 4 weeks. Sweet taste; mix in 8oz water. Track sleep quality (the most subjectively perceptible effect — improvements often noticeable within first week), morning energy, dream quality. If positive sleep response, continue; if minimal effect, may increase to 5g.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Comprehensive glycine protocol:**\n- AM: 3g glycine with breakfast (collagen / methylation support)\n- PM: 3g glycine with dinner\n- Pre-bed: 3g glycine ~30 minutes before sleep (sleep architecture)\n- Total: 9g/day across three doses\n\n**Pair with collagen / gelatin** for synergistic collagen support (collagen provides additional glycine plus other collagen amino acids — proline, hydroxyproline). Bovine collagen 10–20g/day or bone broth provide substantial complementary intake.\n\n**Pair with magnesium glycinate** (the glycine moiety in glycinate provides additional glycine alongside elemental magnesium; complementary).\n\n**Pair with NAC + selenium** for comprehensive glutathione pathway support (NAC provides cysteine — the rate-limiting glutathione substrate; glycine provides the third glutathione amino acid; selenium supports glutathione peroxidase).\n\n## The Modern Diet Glycine Gap\n\nThe ancestral human diet — whole-animal consumption including skin, connective tissue, bones (broth), and organ meats — provided substantial glycine intake. Modern muscle-meat-focused diets are systematically deficient: muscle meat is high in methionine (which competes with glycine in methylation) and relatively low in glycine.\n\nThe practical implication: most users on conventional Western diets are operating in glycine-suboptimal range. Supplementation closes the gap. Bone broth, gelatin desserts, slow-cooked tough cuts (with connective tissue), skin-on chicken — all contribute glycine but most users don't eat enough to meet need.\n\nFor carnivore-diet users: the diet provides substantial glycine if it includes connective tissue, bone broth, organ meats, and skin-on cuts — but pure muscle-meat carnivore is glycine-deficient and supplementation is rational.\n\n## Sleep Architecture — The Subjectively Strongest Effect\n\nThe 3g pre-bed glycine sleep effect is one of the better-documented sleep supplement effects. The mechanism appears to be dual:\n\n1. **Direct neurotransmitter effect** — glycine receptors mediate inhibitory signaling in spinal cord and brainstem\n2. **Peripheral vasodilation** producing core body temperature drop — the body cools as part of sleep onset; glycine's modest vasodilation supports this thermoregulatory transition\n\nSubjective effects users typically notice:\n- Easier sleep onset\n- Reduced middle-of-night awakening\n- More vivid dreams\n- Improved morning energy / reduced grogginess\n\nThe effect is mild compared to pharmaceutical sleep aids but has zero abuse potential, no dependence, no morning hangover, and pairs well with magnesium glycinate and other sleep-supportive interventions.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, tablet, or powder. **Powder is substantially more cost-effective** at typical 5–10g/day doses; mixes easily in water; naturally sweet (does not require flavoring or sweetener for palatability). Pre-bed dosing for sleep priority; split AM/PM/pre-bed for comprehensive use.\n\n## Synergies\n**Magnesium glycinate:** complementary (the glycine in glycinate provides modest additional glycine; supplementing pure glycine on top boosts total intake). **Magnesium L-threonate / malate:** complementary mineral support without glycine duplication. **L-theanine:** complementary calming via different mechanism (alpha-wave / glutamate modulation vs glycine receptor inhibition). **Melatonin:** complementary sleep architecture mechanism. **Collagen / gelatin:** complementary (provides additional glycine plus other collagen amino acids). **NAC + selenium:** complementary glutathione pathway support. **Vitamin C:** collagen synthesis cofactor; supports glycine's collagen role.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\n**Yamadera 2007 (n=11 healthy adults with sleep complaints, 3g glycine pre-bed):** improved subjective sleep quality, reduced daytime sleepiness. **Bannai 2012 (n=15 healthy adults, 3g glycine pre-bed):** improved sleep quality and PSG-measured sleep architecture. Multiple smaller studies extending the sleep effects. Glutathione substrate role and methylation buffer role established mechanistically rather than via dedicated RCTs.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized — glycine's roles in protein synthesis, methylation, glutathione synthesis, bile acid conjugation, and neurotransmission are textbook biology. Clinical evidence: sleep architecture has the most direct RCT support; collagen / methylation / glutathione support is mechanistically grounded but not RCT-validated as supplementation outcomes. Long human dietary exposure history establishes excellent safety baseline.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid mechanistic foundation across multiple distinct biological roles; sleep architecture RCT evidence at 3g pre-bed; collagen / methylation / glutathione roles textbook-established; long dietary exposure history. Anecdote: extensive use in foundational supplement protocols; sleep effects often subjectively perceptible within days; multifunctional benefits accumulate over months. Decision frame: foundational supplement with multiple use cases; cost-effective; excellent tolerability; pairs naturally with magnesium glycinate, collagen, NAC, and broader foundational pillar; particularly relevant for users on muscle-meat-focused diets without compensating connective-tissue / bone-broth intake; carnivore-diet users specifically should consider supplementation if not consuming whole-animal cuts with connective tissue.",
