    mechanism:
      "Acetylated derivative of the amino acid cysteine — the acetyl group provides chemical stability and substantially improved oral bioavailability vs free cysteine, while in vivo metabolism cleaves the acetyl to release cysteine for downstream use. The compound has been a clinical pharmaceutical for decades — IV NAC is the standard antidote for acetaminophen overdose; inhaled NAC is a mucolytic for cystic fibrosis and other respiratory conditions; oral NAC has substantial off-label use in psychiatric, hepatic, fertility, and longevity contexts. **Mechanism — glutathione precursor (the central role)**: glutathione is the body's master intracellular antioxidant, a tripeptide of cysteine + glutamate + glycine. **Cysteine is the rate-limiting substrate for glutathione synthesis** — the other two amino acids are abundant; cysteine availability constrains glutathione production. NAC supplementation provides cysteine substrate, supporting glutathione synthesis and the entire glutathione-dependent antioxidant network. Glutathione's roles include: (1) direct ROS neutralization, (2) cofactor for glutathione peroxidase (selenium-dependent enzyme), (3) cofactor for glutathione S-transferases (Phase II liver detoxification), (4) regeneration of vitamins C and E from oxidized forms, (5) protein S-glutathionylation as a redox-signaling mechanism. **Mechanism — direct antioxidant**: NAC itself has direct ROS-scavenging activity beyond its glutathione substrate role; the free thiol (-SH) group reacts with reactive oxygen and nitrogen species. **Mechanism — mucolytic (the classical pharmaceutical role)**: NAC breaks disulfide bonds in mucus glycoproteins, reducing mucus viscosity. The mechanism underlies the inhaled NAC use in cystic fibrosis and chronic respiratory conditions, and the oral NAC use as adjunct in chronic bronchitis. **Mechanism — acetaminophen overdose antidote (the FDA-approved clinical use)**: acetaminophen overdose depletes hepatic glutathione, allowing toxic NAPQI metabolite accumulation that produces hepatic necrosis. NAC restores glutathione substrate, allowing detoxification of NAPQI. IV NAC administered within ~10 hours of acetaminophen overdose is highly effective; later administration has reduced efficacy. **Mechanism — psychiatric applications (emerging evidence base)**: substantial research interest in NAC for psychiatric conditions including OCD (Berk 2008, Sarris 2015), trichotillomania (Grant 2009), substance use disorders (Asevedo 2014), bipolar depression (Berk 2008), and schizophrenia. Mechanism likely involves glutamate modulation (NAC modulates the cystine-glutamate antiporter) and glutathione antioxidant support in oxidative-stress-related psychiatric conditions. **Mechanism — fertility (PCOS context)**: NAC has emerging evidence for fertility support in PCOS women — improved ovulation, insulin sensitivity, embryo quality (Salehpour 2007, multiple subsequent trials). **Mechanism — hepatoprotective**: beyond acetaminophen overdose, NAC has broader hepatoprotective use in fatty liver disease, alcohol-induced liver damage, and hepatic detoxification support. **FDA regulatory status — the 2020-2022 ambiguity (worth honestly framing)**: in 2020, the FDA issued warning letters challenging NAC's status as a dietary supplement under DSHEA, citing prior approval as a drug (Mucomyst, 1963) — DSHEA generally prohibits drugs from being marketed as dietary supplements. The challenge produced significant industry concern. In 2022, the FDA announced enforcement discretion for NAC dietary supplements, allowing continued sale while not formally resolving the regulatory question. **NAC remains widely available as an OTC supplement as of catalog last update**, but the regulatory status is technically ambiguous. The pharmaceutical version (Mucomyst, generic acetylcysteine) requires prescription in most jurisdictions. **Pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability ~10% (modest — most oral cysteine is rapidly metabolized in liver before reaching systemic circulation); plasma peak ~1 hour; effects on glutathione synthesis sustained 6–12 hours per dose; commonly dosed BID for sustained effect.",
